[3] Latvia: domestic swine and wild boar, spread
Date: Tue 22 Jul 2014
Source: Global Post, Agence France-Presse (AFP) report [edited]
http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/afp/140722/latvia-extends-emergency-zone-african-swine-fever


Latvia extends emergency zone for African swine fever
-----------------------------------------------------
On Tuesday [22 Jul 2014], Latvia declared a state of emergency in a 2nd area of this Baltic EU state as efforts continued to contain an outbreak of deadly African swine fever in its pig population.

The extension of the emergency quarantine zone means large swathes of Latvia's borders with Belarus, Estonia, Lithuania, and Russia now fall within it. Inside the zone, animals cannot be moved between farms, [access to infected farms is restricted], and inspectors can order culls on the spot.

The government also approved measures Tuesday [22 Jul 2014] including compensation for small farmers who have had to slaughter diseased pigs and broader rights for veterinary inspectors in accessing private property.

Prime Minister Laimdota Straujuma warned Tuesday [22 Jul 2014] of "major losses" to the farming sector unless the disease is contained, with Russia and Belarus already slapping blanket bans on Latvian pork products.

Straujuma blamed wild boar crossing in from Russia for Latvia's 1st-ever outbreak of the disease, detected on 26 Jun 2014. Since then, a total of 26 wild boar and 19 pigs on 11 farms have tested positive for it, and 185 pigs have been put down.

Experts believe it first emanated from Belarus, and was also confirmed earlier this year [2014] in wild boar in fellow European Union members Poland and Lithuania.

--
